The init command creates .drift/ (containing state.xml and baselines/), and if main.drift.xml does not already exist, writes a starter template with a single example spec. It also creates .drift/.gitignore containing "user-settings.xml" and "state.lock" to prevent accidental commits of per-user theme preferences and runtime lock files. The output message instructs the user to edit main.drift.xml, place markers, and run drift skill. Init is idempotent at the CLI level: if .drift/state.xml already exists (the project is already initialized), init prints "Already initialized. Run `drift todo` to check state." with exit code 0 and does NOT modify any existing files. To forcibly reinitialize, the user must delete .drift/state.xml (or .drift/) by hand — drift provides no command to do this, by design (protecting against accidental state loss). See init_idempotent for the orchestrator-level enforcement.